# Project Memory Maintenance

When working in this repository, do not rely only on chat context.

If you discover durable project knowledge, recurring pitfalls, setup details, test quirks, architecture conventions, data format details, or workflow rules that future agents should know, propose an update to `AGENTS.md` or `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`.

## What should be remembered

Examples of durable knowledge:

- correct setup, test, build, and app start commands
- known test pitfalls or hanging commands
- CI-specific behavior
- data format rules
- important input/output mappings
- repository directory semantics
- architecture conventions
- generated/reference-only directories
- customer terminology relevant to implementation
- recurring bugs and their root causes
- rules that prevent accidental regressions

## How to update instructions

- Prefer updating existing sections instead of creating duplicates.
- Keep entries concise and factual.
- Base updates on observed project evidence.
- Mark uncertain items as assumptions.
- Do not include secrets, credentials, tokens, private customer data, or raw sensitive sample data.
- Do not add one-off task details that are unlikely to matter later.

## End-of-task requirement

At the end of every non-trivial task, include:

```text
Project memory updates:
- No update needed.

or:
Project memory updates:
- Proposed update to AGENTS.md: ...
- Proposed update to .cursor/rules/...

If the update is small, safe, and clearly useful, you may edit the instruction files, but the user must review the diff before commit.

